00:45:40,499 --> 00:45:43,740
the same. That's a special and simple case.

1117
00:45:43,740 --> 00:45:46,829
All right, but we didn't, I just

1118
00:45:46,829 --> 00:45:49,919
wanted to illustrate some of the equations here.

1119
00:45:51,100 --> 00:45:53,100
And

1120
00:45:53,919 --> 00:45:55,919
incidentally,

1121
00:45:56,080 --> 00:45:58,080
this equation over here

1122
00:46:01,339 --> 00:46:03,249
is equivalent to another equation of

1123
00:46:03,249 --> 00:46:05,160
physics. Anybody know what it is?

1124
00:46:08,959 --> 00:46:10,959
The Schrodinger equation.

1125
00:46:11,379 --> 00:46:13,560
The Schrodinger equation is an equation

1126
00:46:13,740 --> 00:46:15,740
for a wave, and

1127
00:46:16,560 --> 00:46:18,469
this tells you the time

1128
00:46:18,469 --> 00:46:20,379
dependence of the wave, the frequency.

1129
00:46:20,939 --> 00:46:25,099
This tells you the space dependence of the wave. The Schrodinger

1130
00:46:25,099 --> 00:46:29,259
equation is exactly an equation for the relationship between the time

1131
00:46:29,399 --> 00:46:31,339
dependence of a wave and

1132
00:46:31,339 --> 00:46:32,629
the space dependence of the wave.

1133
00:46:32,629 --> 00:46:33,919
We will come back to it.

1134
00:46:34,419 --> 00:46:37,600
But this is just the Schrodinger equation in a

1135
00:46:38,580 --> 00:46:40,580
slightly disguised form.

1136
00:46:41,339 --> 00:46:43,339
Or better yet, if you knew the Schrodinger equation,

1137
00:46:43,740 --> 00:46:46,039
and you said, supposing I had a wave

1138
00:46:46,039 --> 00:46:48,339
of a given frequency that had a given wavelength,

1139
00:46:48,879 --> 00:46:51,569
what would the equation tell me about the relation

1140
00:46:51,569 --> 00:46:54,259
between wavelength and frequency? And it would be exactly this.

1141
00:46:56,200 --> 00:46:58,620
Okay, so that's the Schrodinger equation in a nutshell.

1142
00:47:02,080 --> 00:47:04,979
Can the phase velocity go faster than light?

1143
00:47:04,979 --> 00:47:06,979
Yes.

1144
00:47:07,859 --> 00:47:09,959
But the phase velocity as a

1145
00:47:09,959 --> 00:47:12,060
rule carries no information with it.

1146
00:47:13,740 --> 00:47:16,939
You can't send information faster than the group velocity.

1147
00:47:17,919 --> 00:47:20,919
Phase velocity doesn't really carry any

1148
00:47:22,299 --> 00:47:24,220
information with it.

1149
00:47:24,220 --> 00:47:25,419
So,

1150
00:47:25,419 --> 00:47:28,139
we'll come back to that. It's a technical issue that

1151
00:47:28,139 --> 00:47:30,859
we don't need to deal with right at this moment.

1152
00:47:32,419 --> 00:47:34,419
Okay.

1153
00:47:34,520 --> 00:47:36,520
Let's see.

1154
00:47:37,200 --> 00:47:39,259
Let's go on a little bit more with waves.

1155
00:47:39,419 --> 00:47:41,359
There are one or two

1156
00:47:41,359 --> 00:47:43,299
other concepts about waves that are

1157
00:47:43,740 --> 00:47:45,740
necessary.

1158
00:47:49,600 --> 00:47:53,729
And, you know, there's a lot of technical detail that I'm getting

1159
00:47:53,729 --> 00:47:57,859
into, but every single piece of it is really very central or important.

1160
00:47:58,680 --> 00:48:00,200
Okay.

1161
00:48:00,200 --> 00:48:03,620
We will be interested in waves moving in infinite space.

1162
00:48:05,000 --> 00:48:07,700
But I use the word infinite space,

1163
00:48:08,520 --> 00:48:10,520
infinite, infinity.

1164
00:48:11,919 --> 00:48:13,680
Computers don't like infinity.

1165
00:48:13,680 --> 00:48:15,680
And if

1166
00:48:17,799 --> 00:48:20,099
physics is the art of writing

1167
00:48:20,099 --> 00:48:22,399
equations that computers can solve in principle,

1168
00:48:22,399 --> 00:48:27,909
it is necessary to always remove the infinities and write

1169
00:48:27,909 --> 00:48:33,419
the equations for finite systems first, and then take a limit.

1170
00:48:34,480 --> 00:48:37,669
All right. So in studying quantum mechanics, waves,

1171
00:48:37,669 --> 00:48:40,859
quantum field theory, particle physics, and so forth,

1172
00:48:41,379 --> 00:48:43,379
it's necessary in the back of your mind,

1173
00:48:43,680 --> 00:48:47,539
to get rid first round of everything that's infinite,

1174
00:48:47,539 --> 00:48:51,399
and state the problems as if everything were finite.

1175
00:48:51,399 --> 00:48:53,639
And in particular, what I have in

1176
00:48:53,639 --> 00:48:55,879
mind now is the extent of space itself.

1177
00:48:57,660 --> 00:48:59,660
So one way of...

1178
00:49:00,140 --> 00:49:02,130
What I want you to think about

1179
00:49:02,130 --> 00:49:04,120
now is a wave moving in one dimension.

1180
00:49:05,500 --> 00:49:07,439
Three dimensions is really no different than

1181
00:49:07,439 --> 00:49:09,379
one dimension, except there are three of them.

1182
00:49:10,279 --> 00:49:13,359
So let's concentrate on one-dimensional wave motion.

1183
00:49:13,680 --> 00:49:16,729
It could be a violin string, it could

1184
00:49:16,729 --> 00:49:19,779
be a rope being wiggled back and forth,

1185
00:49:19,779 --> 00:49:21,439
or it could just be a wave

1186
00:49:21,439 --> 00:49:23,100
in a mathematical universe of one dimension.

1187
00:49:24,100 --> 00:49:27,110
One way of getting rid of the infinity

1188
00:49:27,110 --> 00:49:30,120
of space would be to make the wave

1189
00:49:30,799 --> 00:49:33,500
only propagate on a region of

1190
00:49:35,000 --> 00:49:37,000
length L.

1191
00:49:37,359 --> 00:49:40,509
For example, by holding down the wave at this end, holding

1192
00:49:40,509 --> 00:49:43,660
down your string at this end, just like a violin string,

1193
00:49:43,680 --> 00:49:45,999
the string is held down, holding it down at

1194
00:49:45,999 --> 00:49:48,319
this end, you can have all sorts of waves.

1195
00:49:49,180 --> 00:49:52,229
And the waves move, and they bounce off. When

1196
00:49:52,229 --> 00:49:55,279
they get to the end, they bounce off and reflect,

1197
00:49:55,480 --> 00:49:57,480
and they go back and forth, and back and forth.

1198
00:49:58,419 --> 00:50:01,399
That's a perfectly good way to describe things.

1199
00:50:01,940 --> 00:50:04,790
The problem with this kind of, let's call

1200
00:50:04,790 --> 00:50:07,640
it boundary condition, this is called the boundary condition,

1201
00:50:08,200 --> 00:50:10,789
namely, that waves, when they get to the

1202
00:50:10,789 --> 00:50:13,379
end, reflect. It's called a reflecting boundary condition.

1203
00:50:13,680 --> 00:50:17,279
The problem with it is it violates one of the

1204
00:50:17,279 --> 00:50:20,879
important conservation laws of physics. What would that conservation law be?

1205
00:50:23,160 --> 00:50:28,500
Momentum. After all, if the momentum of a wave is,

1206
00:50:32,240 --> 00:50:34,740
it's a vector quantity, it points in a direction.

1207
00:50:35,919 --> 00:50:39,789
If a wave is moving along this, here's a little wave,

1208
00:50:39,789 --> 00:50:43,660
it's moving along this axis, its momentum is pointing to the left.

1209
00:50:43,680 --> 00:50:45,880
It's pointing to the right. When it gets

1210
00:50:45,880 --> 00:50:48,080
to the end, it bounces off and reflects.

1211
00:50:48,759 --> 00:50:52,000
So, the momentum has changed sign.

1212
00:50:53,200 --> 00:50:56,660
Okay, the momentum has changed sign, the momentum is not conserved.

1213
00:50:56,660 --> 00:51:00,120
That's okay. There's nothing wrong with it. You can study it.

1214
00:51:00,919 --> 00:51:04,779
But if you want to keep track of things like momentum

1215
00:51:04,779 --> 00:51:08,640
conservation, there's a smarter thing you can do. It goes as follows.

1216
00:51:09,799 --> 00:51:13,440
Imagine this line is such that we identify

1217
00:51:13,680 --> 00:51:17,029
the beginning and the end. Now, we can

1218
00:51:17,029 --> 00:51:20,379
do that by replacing the line by a circle.

1219
00:51:20,379 --> 00:51:23,140
It doesn't have to be a legitimate geometric circle.

1220
00:51:23,640 --> 00:51:24,859
Just

1221
00:51:24,859 --> 00:51:27,259
mathematically, we connect the beginning back to

1222
00:51:27,259 --> 00:51:29,660
the end. So we go on a cycle.

1223
00:51:30,480 --> 00:51:33,520
And so as we move from here to here to

1224
00:51:33,520 --> 00:51:36,560
here, we can imagine we start here, move along here, and

1225
00:51:37,440 --> 00:51:39,580
in this magic line, when you get to

1226
00:51:39,580 --> 00:51:41,720
the other end, you come back to the beginning.

1227
00:51:42,460 --> 00:51:43,640
That's a closed,

1228
00:51:43,640 --> 00:51:47,009
I don't want to call it a circle because I

1229
00:51:47,009 --> 00:51:50,379
don't mean to imply it's a circle in two dimensions.

1230
00:51:50,379 --> 00:51:52,379
I just want to imply that it's periodic.

1231
00:51:52,980 --> 00:51:54,980
Periodic is the term for this.

1232
00:51:55,080 --> 00:51:57,859
Periodic space. Now you can imagine a wave

1233
00:51:59,580 --> 00:52:01,580
which is moving along,

1234
00:52:02,160 --> 00:52:04,160
moving along here,

1235
00:52:04,839 --> 00:52:06,869
and when it comes to the end over

1236
00:52:06,869 --> 00:52:08,900
here, what does it do? It just keeps going.

1237
00:52:10,000 --> 00:52:11,800
Right? It just keeps going. It doesn't care

1238
00:52:11,800 --> 00:52:13,600
about that point. That point is not a square.

1239
00:52:13,640 --> 00:52:14,640
It's not a special point anymore.

1240
00:52:14,640 --> 00:52:17,749
And so the wave just keeps cycling around,

1241
00:52:17,749 --> 00:52:20,859
cycling around, cycling around, and the momentum is conserved.

1242
00:52:21,400 --> 00:52:23,660
It doesn't suddenly reflect into the

1243
00:52:23,660 --> 00:52:25,920
other direction. In terms of this picture,

1244
00:52:25,920 --> 00:52:28,040
you can just imagine when the wave gets

1245
00:52:28,040 --> 00:52:30,160
to this end, it reappears at this end.

1246
00:52:30,160 --> 00:52:31,920
And it just keeps going to the

1247
00:52:31,920 --> 00:52:33,680
right if it were going to the right.

1248
00:52:33,680 --> 00:52:35,469
It goes to the left if it were

1249
00:52:35,469 --> 00:52:37,259
going to the left, and just keeps going forever.

1250
00:52:37,839 --> 00:52:40,669
With this trick, with this mathematical trick

1251
00:52:40,669 --> 00:52:43,500
of replacing space by a periodic space,

1252
00:52:43,640 --> 00:52:45,989
we can first of all get rid

1253
00:52:45,989 --> 00:52:48,339
of the infinity in the size of space,

1254
00:52:49,319 --> 00:52:51,319
feed it into a computer,

1255
00:52:51,940 --> 00:52:55,000
and we can get rid of

1256
00:52:55,000 --> 00:52:58,060
the problem of momentum, of non-momentum conservation.

1257
00:52:59,259 --> 00:53:01,259
Momentum is now conserved.

1258
00:53:01,660 --> 00:53:03,660
But there is a cost.

1259
00:53:04,080 --> 00:53:06,780
I don't know that it's a cost, but it's

1260
00:53:06,780 --> 00:53:09,480
a fact. The fact is that in such a world,

1261
00:53:10,660 --> 00:53:12,660
momentum is quantized.

1262
00:53:12,660 --> 00:53:15,660
Now I don't mean in the sense that,

1263
00:53:17,680 --> 00:53:20,969
well, it is that momentum only

1264
00:53:20,969 --> 00:53:24,259
comes in discrete multiples of a unit.

1265
00:53:24,259 --> 00:53:27,140
And it's useful to work

1266
00:53:28,720 --> 00:53:30,809
in understanding quantum fields, their

1267
00:53:30,809 --> 00:53:32,899
relation to particles, and so forth.

1268
00:53:32,899 --> 00:53:36,089
It's useful to remember that the momentum comes in

1269
00:53:36,089 --> 00:53:39,279
discrete multiples of something. So let's see how that works.

1270
00:53:42,660 --> 00:53:46,660
Well, first of all, it's obvious that the wavelength,

1271
00:53:48,160 --> 00:53:52,480
an integer number of waves, must fit.

1272
00:53:52,480 --> 00:53:55,080
Let's give this distance around here a

1273
00:53:55,080 --> 00:53:57,680
name. Let's call it L. L for length.

1274
00:53:58,500 --> 00:54:00,500
If it were a circle, it would be the circumference.

1275
00:54:00,680 --> 00:54:03,620
But let's just call it L. The total distance

1276
00:54:03,620 --> 00:54:06,560
around from beginning back to beginning again. Call it L.

1277
00:54:07,160 --> 00:54:08,420
All right.

1278
00:54:08,420 --> 00:54:10,500
If we're going to put a wave in there, and let's

1279
00:54:10,500 --> 00:54:12,580
say now that it's a wave, a sine or a cosine,

1280
00:54:12,580 --> 00:54:14,580
wave or whatever,

1281
00:54:15,000 --> 00:54:17,490
an integer number of wavelengths

1282
00:54:17,490 --> 00:54:19,980
has to fit onto the circle.

1283
00:54:21,000 --> 00:54:24,200
That means that the wavelength has to be

1284
00:54:24,200 --> 00:54:27,400
equal to the length around divided by an integer.

1285
00:54:28,620 --> 00:54:32,799
Okay, divided by an integer. So the wavelength must be

1286
00:54:34,660 --> 00:54:36,660
the total distance around

1287
00:54:37,380 --> 00:54:39,579
divided by some integer. I don't want

1288
00:54:39,579 --> 00:54:41,779
to call the integer n. Let's see.

1289
00:54:41,779 --> 00:54:42,279
Um-

1290
00:54:42,280 --> 00:54:44,280
I'll call it capital N.

1291
00:54:46,240 --> 00:54:47,780
Capital N.

1292
00:54:47,780 --> 00:54:50,040
Little n will be reserved for something else.

1293
00:54:52,100 --> 00:54:55,170
So the wavelength is necessarily the

1294
00:54:55,170 --> 00:54:58,240
total distance around divided by n.

1295
00:54:58,420 --> 00:55:00,480
Now that means the

1296
00:55:00,480 --> 00:55:02,540
wavelength comes in discrete possibilities.

1297
00:55:03,900 --> 00:55:06,650
It can be L. It can be L over 2. It

1298
00:55:06,650 --> 00:55:09,400
can be L over 3. It can be L over 4.

1299
00:55:09,400 --> 00:55:10,780
But it can't be L

1300
00:55:10,780 --> 00:55:12,160
times the square root of 1.

1301
00:55:12,160 --> 00:55:13,660
It can't be L times the square root of

1302
00:55:13,660 --> 00:55:15,160
2 or L divided by the square root of 2.

1303
00:55:16,240 --> 00:55:18,920
An integer number of waves just won't fit in here.

1304
00:55:18,920 --> 00:55:21,270
In other words, if you tried to put a wavelength of

1305
00:55:21,270 --> 00:55:23,620
the wrong wavelength in here, by the time you got back,

1306
00:55:24,000 --> 00:55:25,960
the wave wouldn't match with what it

1307
00:55:25,960 --> 00:55:27,920
was supposed to be at the beginning.

1308
00:55:28,759 --> 00:55:32,879
Okay, so that tells you that wavelengths come in discrete

1309
00:55:34,660 --> 00:55:37,960
possibilities with the integer appearing in the denominator.

1310
00:55:38,500 --> 00:55:40,859
Now we had an equation here somewhere

1311
00:55:40,859 --> 00:55:42,000
for momentum.

1312
00:55:42,000 --> 00:55:45,200
Momentum in terms of wavelength.

1313
00:55:45,200 --> 00:55:46,200
What was it?

1314
00:55:47,200 --> 00:55:52,000
Momentum was equal h bar.

1315
00:55:52,000 --> 00:55:54,000
h over lambda?

1316
00:55:55,300 --> 00:55:57,300
Yes, h over lambda.

1317
00:56:05,000 --> 00:56:07,000
P is equal to h over lambda.

1318
00:56:07,000 --> 00:56:11,000
So now this is also telling us that momenta come

1319
00:56:11,000 --> 00:56:14,000
in discrete possibilities.

1320
00:56:15,000 --> 00:56:19,850
The momentum of any quantum must satisfy the

1321
00:56:19,850 --> 00:56:24,700
constraint that it's h divided by an allowable wavelength.

1322
00:56:24,700 --> 00:56:27,350
So the allowable momenta of

1323
00:56:27,350 --> 00:56:30,000
quanta, the allowable momenta of electrons,

1324
00:56:30,000 --> 00:56:34,000
the allowable momenta of photons, the allowable

1325
00:56:34,000 --> 00:56:38,000
momentum of anything in this one-dimensional world

1326
00:56:38,000 --> 00:56:41,500
has to be h divided by, okay, let's

1327
00:56:41,500 --> 00:56:45,000
work it out, that's h divided by lambda.

1328
00:56:45,000 --> 00:56:49,000
That means n divided by l.

1329
00:56:49,000 --> 00:56:53,000
I turned lambda upside down, n over l.

1330
00:56:53,000 --> 00:56:54,000
And what does it say?

1331
00:56:54,000 --> 00:56:56,500
It says the momenta come in

1332
00:56:56,500 --> 00:56:59,000
discrete multiples of a basic unit,

1333
00:56:59,000 --> 00:57:02,500
and the basic unit is Planck's

1334
00:57:02,500 --> 00:57:06,000
constant divided by the total distance around.

1335
00:57:06,000 --> 00:57:07,000
Okay.

1336
00:57:08,000 --> 00:57:12,000
There's a neat fact.

1337
00:57:12,000 --> 00:57:16,500
If you put a particle on a wire, and the wire

1338
00:57:16,500 --> 00:57:21,000
is a circular wire, a bead, a bead on a wire,

1339
00:57:21,000 --> 00:57:25,000
that bead can only have momenta which

1340
00:57:25,000 --> 00:57:29,000
are discrete multiples of 1 over l.

1341
00:57:29,000 --> 00:57:32,000
Not n over l, n is the multiple.

1342
00:57:32,000 --> 00:57:33,000
1 over l.

1343
00:57:33,000 --> 00:57:37,000
1 over the length of the wire.

1344
00:57:37,000 --> 00:57:42,000
Now, of course, h is a very small number,

1345
00:57:42,000 --> 00:57:47,500
and the l, if l is a

1346
00:57:47,500 --> 00:57:53,000
big macroscopic length of wire or something,

1347
00:57:53,000 --> 00:57:56,000
1 over l is a very small number.

1348
00:57:56,000 --> 00:58:01,000
And so the quanta, the separation between different values,

1349
00:58:01,000 --> 00:58:05,000
different allowed values of the momenta is very small.

1350
00:58:05,000 --> 00:58:06,000
You can get, ohm,

1351
00:58:06,000 --> 00:58:08,000
if l is large and h is

1352
00:58:08,000 --> 00:58:10,000
small, you can get almost any number.

1353
00:58:10,000 --> 00:58:12,500
Not almost any number, but you can

1354
00:58:12,500 --> 00:58:15,000
get a very dense collection of possible numbers.

1355
00:58:15,000 --> 00:58:16,000
All right?

1356
00:58:16,000 --> 00:58:19,000
But, okay.

1357
00:58:19,000 --> 00:58:23,000
That's the quantization of momentum in

1358
00:58:23,000 --> 00:58:27,000
a world in which everything is periodic.

1359
00:58:27,000 --> 00:58:28,000
Question.

1360
00:58:28,000 --> 00:58:29,000
Yeah.

1361
00:58:29,000 --> 00:58:30,000
Are we talking about the total momentum

1362
00:58:30,000 --> 00:58:31,000
of the wave or a period of time?

1363
00:58:31,000 --> 00:58:32,000
Total momentum, no.

1364
00:58:32,000 --> 00:58:35,000
Total momentum of the object.

1365
00:58:35,000 --> 00:58:40,000
Total momentum of any quantum.

1366
00:58:40,000 --> 00:58:43,500
Now, if every quantum has to have an

1367
00:58:43,500 --> 00:58:47,000
integer multiple of this basic unit of momentum,

1368
00:58:47,000 --> 00:58:49,500
then any number of quanta also have

1369
00:58:49,500 --> 00:58:52,000
to have an integer multiple of it.

1370
00:58:52,000 --> 00:58:53,000
All right?

1371
00:58:53,000 --> 00:58:57,500
You might have, each quantum is identified

1372
00:58:57,500 --> 00:59:02,000
